In this code snippet, the `filterDataById` function takes the data object and an ID as parameters. It recursively searches for the ID in the data object and its `teamMembers` array. If the ID is found, it returns the corresponding node. In the example provided, calling `filterDataById(data, "test2")` will return the node with ID "test2" and its corresponding details.

To achieve the desired result where the filtered data retains the tree structure but only contains the filtered node, we can modify the `filterDataById` function as follows:

```javascript
function filterDataById(data, id) {
  if (data.id === id) {
    return data;
  }

  for (var i = 0; i < data.teamMembers.length; i++) {
    if (data.teamMembers[i].id === id) {
      return {
        id: data.teamMembers[i].id
      };
    }
  }

  for (var i = 0; i < data.teamMembers.length; i++) {
    var filteredNode = filterDataById(data.teamMembers[i], id);
    if (filteredNode) {
      return {
        id: data.id,
        teamMembers: [filteredNode]
      };
    }
  }

  return null;
}

